What Makes a Good Infographic? (piktochart)

I feel like college doesn't teach students /how to disagree/. By /how to
disagree/ I mean how to deal with disgreement, or how to resolve
disagreements in a civil manner. In a writing argument, I felt as
though everyone in the class was learning how to be persuasive about
whatever it is they think is true, that is, how to make it sound like
you're right. Managing /real/ disagreement strikes me as precisely the
activity that teaches people how to recognize when they are /wrong/. If
we are not practicing to recognize when we are wrong, but are instead
only taught how to appear persuasive (often arguing against people who
aren't in the classroom), it would follow that one never learns the
appropriate way to react when in a disagreement, possibly sensitive?

I have had this thought before, but it has just now come back to me: I
think it best in any situation not to state a disagreement if you are
not prepared to explain yourself.

Have been spending valuable time on the internet reading articles and
things on civil discourse, intellectual humility and scientific
humility. I want to be able to describe the feelings that I have for
the idea of 'humility,' but I am not so sure this is exactly the right
way to describe the attitutes to which I am inclined. This began in my
research of the Intellectual Dark Web and controversial speakers,
first focusing on free speech and then narrowed into civil discourse.
*** 2018-06-24 Sunday
[2018-06-24 Sun]

Finishing up my rhetorical analysis, I think the main points that I am
trying to make are that Dr. Helms is influenced by postmodern
thought. How much he ascribes to the messages is probably what I
should focus on primarily, as opposed to the actual validity of the
theory itself. Leaving the opinion for the op-ed.

What has he done though, with respect to postmodern thought. The idea
that clarity is a myth? Why, then, has he resorted to stating that
sometimes we must take things on faith and not remain skeptical? 

Today I am going to wing this motherfucking project like a
motherfucking boss. Just kidding we will have to see how it turns out
but I feel like I am on to something. Don't know quite what it is but
it sure seems that postmodernism is a load of bullshit. Okay so how
should I start off the argument? Will need to make a statement of
rhetorical analysis of Dr. Helms. I have some data from a previous
class, could go off of the template from the book about Obama:

#+BEGIN_QUOTE
Many people admire the vision and eloquence of President Obama; others
are put off by his often distant tone and his “professorial” stance. A
close look at several of his speeches will illuminate both sides of
this debate.
#+END_QUOTE

I may look at Dr. Helms and say that some people admire the "vision
and eloquence," or something like this. I could probably do something
like, instead of eloquence and vision I could do: well Dr. Helms is
very polite in class, perhaps this would be one. He is very outspoken,
passionate and motivated. Obviously he loves his job, I think that is
clear. Devotion is a good term. On the other hand, I think he is
fundamentally mistaken about some really core ideologies that he holds
(if he indeed holds the ones that I think he does). 

The public issue that I will be doing is postmodernism and its
influence on the universities. The stakeholder will be Dr. Helms, as
stated, and my rhetorical analysis claim could be that some people
admire Dr. Helms' engaging and passionate teaching style, some are put
off by the postmodern philosophy that has infected the university
Humanities departments. Nah, perhaps that second part would instead
focus on just how Dr. Helms seems to cause distress in students who
really take the course seriously. No, I must not say this either in
the event that this comes across as belittling toward my classmates. I
am thinking that what I mean to say is probably something along the
lines of how Dr. Helms teaching style does not lend itself to much
skepticism. That is, the classroom environment does not set an
atmosphere of civility and respect for the individual.

Should I relate this back to the overall problem of Postmodernism that
I am trying to address? It would have to be something like how the
postmodern philosophies are affecting the classroom, or no, it must
not involve my opinion so it would be more on the views of Dr. Helms
and whether or not he displays any symptoms (lol) of postmodern
thinking. 

I really don't mean this in any sort of negative way, it just so
happens that this philosophy has seemingly been the very root from
which I have had my troubles with the English department at TCU.

** 2018-W26
*** 2018-06-25 Monday
[2018-06-25 Mon]

Talking with Dr. Helms today
- I care and think alot about argumentative writing
- does my epistemology conflict with the nature of this course
- truth vs Truth and selective vs. genuine skepticism
- /persuasion/ is not my goal as a person, seeking Truth is
- "It seems to me like this would be a good idea, what do you think?"
- choosing you as stakeholder, value of two-sided disagreements, mediation
