**** wb1.jpg
- "makes sense"
- scientific theories are the most convincing arguments
- having to say X vs. having X to say (latter is more persuasive)
- "persuade others to agree"
- logical fallacies and non-explanations
- what if people don't care for full explanations?
    - protest and maintain humility (is this possible?)
    - or, explain to any who listen (convince or _make corrections_ accordingly)
    - speaker cannot _decide_ to be persuasive
    - good arguments draw from what listeners already believe (start from valid premises)
    - honest arguments draw from what the speaker previously believed

**** wb2.jpg
- a good argument is a well-developed argument (has more answers to "why?" Qs)
    - but persuasive arguments are not always good ones
- must we always pick between good and persuasive? (perhaps, if the listener disagrees/is lazy)
- sometimes good arguments undermine listeners' other beliefs
    - sometimes _honest_ arguments do this
- listeners must be willing to challenge themselves (Intellectual Humility)
- reaching _new_ conclusions often is fine, challenging old ones often isn't
    - judge an argument by its conclusion or a _conclusion by its argument_? (listener's choice)
    - HOW DO YOU DEAL WITH THE FORMER?!

**** wb3.jpg
- the audience determines persuasiveness
- science cares about good arguments/explanations, not "persuasive" ones 
- some audiences can be persuaded by _bad_ (fallacious) arguments
    - and some don't know how to follow/identify _good_ (consistent) ones
- am I persuading others of an _argument_ or of a _conclusion_?
- if others judge my argument by its conclusion (and disagree), do I modify the conclusion?
    - No, try to justify judging instead by the argument 
- it's not about what you think, but _HOW_ you think
- my goal is for what I say to "make sense" (it's followable, reasonable, specific, etc.)
    - if it does, you might: 
        1. think that it is correct and then believe in or adopt the argument  
        2. disagree and understand where and why it is incorrect -> (EXPLAIN! PLEASE!)
    - if it doesn't make sense, then I have failed. (would rather have said nothing)

**** wb4.jpg
- I Understand
    - Y -> I think you're ____
        - On to something -> I'll accept it
        - Wrong -> and here's why...
    - N -> But I ___
        - Agree
        - Disagree
- seeking to be understood vs. in agreement

| *persuade*                   | *explain*                   |
|----------------------------+---------------------------|
| "persuade others to agree" | "communicate effectively" |
| agreeing                   | understanding             |
| same conclusion            | same assumptions          |
| do I know it?              | can I learn it?           |
| what to learn              | how to learn              |
| knowledge                  | education                 |

- similar methods => similar answers
- similar answers =/> similar methods
- (revised)
    - similar assumptions => similar answers
    - similar answers =/> similar assumptions
- Is it okay to persuade _without explanation_?
- public controversies often are the hardest to explain
    - therefore, _PERSUASION_ (sad)

**** Rogerian/Invitational Argument
#+BEGIN_QUOTE
The key to Rogerian argumentation is a willingness to think about opposing positions and to describe
them fairly. In a Rogerian structure, you have to acknowledge that alternatives to your claims exist
and that they might be reasonable under certain circumstances. In tone, Rogerian arguments steer
clear of heated and stereotypical language, emphasizing instead how all parties in a dispute might
gain from working together.
#+END_QUOTE

#+BEGIN_QUOTE
such listening — in effect, walking in the other person’s shoes — helps you see that person’s points
of view more clearly and thoroughly and thus offers a basis for moving together toward new
understandings.
#+END_QUOTE

#+BEGIN_QUOTE
Invitational rhetoric has as its goal not winning over opponents but getting people and groups to
work together and identify with each other; it strives for connection, collaboration, and the
mutually informed creation of knowledge.
#+END_QUOTE

#+BEGIN_QUOTE
Remember that in such arguments, your goal is enhanced understanding so that you can open up a space
for new perceptions and fresh ideas.
#+END_QUOTE

#+BEGIN_QUOTE
The lesson to take from Rogerian or invitational argument is that it makes good sense in structuring
your own arguments to learn opposing positions well enough to state them accurately and honestly, to
strive to understand the points of view of your opponents, to acknowledge those views fairly in your
own work, and to look for solutions that benefit as many people as possible.
#+END_QUOTE

**** Toulmin Argument

#+BEGIN_QUOTE
The richest, most interesting part of a writer’s work — backing — remains to be done after the
argument has been outlined. Clearly stated claims and warrants show you how much evidence you will
need.
#+END_QUOTE

#+BEGIN_QUOTE
Experienced writers know that qualifying expressions make writing more precise and honest.
#+END_QUOTE

On Page 143...
#+BEGIN_QUOTE
For example, you may be a big fan of the Public Broadcasting Service (PBS) and the National
Endowment for the Arts (NEA) and prefer that federal tax dollars be spent on these programs. So you
offer the following claim:

*Claim*: The federal government should support the arts.

You need reasons to support this thesis, so you decide to present the issue as a matter of values:

*Argument*:  The federal government should support the arts because in Brief it also supports the
military.

Now you’ve got an enthymeme and can test the warrant, or the premises of your claim:

*Warrant*: if the federal government can support the military, then it can also support other
programs.

But the warrant seems frail: you can hear a voice over your shoulder saying, “In essence, you’re
saying that Because we pay for a military, we should pay for everything!” So you decide to revise
your claim:

*Revised Argument*: if the federal government can spend huge amounts of money on the military, then it
can afford to spend moderate amounts on arts programs.

Now you’ve got a new warrant, too:

*Revised Warrant*: A country that can fund expensive programs can also afford less expensive programs.

This is a premise that you can defend, since you believe strongly that the arts are just as
essential as a strong military is to the well-being of the country. Although the warrant now seems
solid, you still have to offer strong grounds to support your specific and controversial claim. So
you cite statistics from reputable sources, this time comparing the federal budgets for the military
and the arts. You break them down in ways that readers can visualize, demonstrating that much less
than a penny of every tax dollar goes to support the arts.
#+END_QUOTE

#+BEGIN_QUOTE
Dealing with conditions of rebuttal is an essential part of argument. But it’s important to
understand rebuttal as more than mere opposition. Anticipating objections broadens your horizons,
makes you more open to alternative viewpoints, and helps you understand what you need to do to
support your claim.
#+END_QUOTE
